def: Of or pertaining to the first Frankish dynasty in Gaul orFrance.-- n.
Issuing or flowing forth; emanating; passing forth into an act,or making itself apparent by an effect; -- said of mental acts; as,an emanant volition.
An herb (Linaria vulgaris) of the Figwort family, having narrowleaves and showy orange and yellow flowers; -- called also butter andeggs, flaxweed, and ramsted.
A large metal pipe made to be extended vertically by sections,and used for discharging water upon burning buildings.
A contemptible or vicious critic.The rancorous and reptile crew of poeticules, who decompose intocriticasters. Swinburne.
A deep pie or pudding made of baked apples, or of sliced breadand apples baked together, with no bottom crust.
from Swear, v.Idle swearing is a cursedness. Chaucer.
A swaggering; vain boasting; ostentation; a bluster. Swift.
